  "prompt": "Why doesn't God do anything?",
  "response": "That's a really profound question that people have grappled with for centuries. There's no single, easy answer, and how someone responds often depends on their personal beliefs and experiences. Here are a few common perspectives:\n\n*   **God is working in ways we don't understand:** This view suggests that God's actions might not be immediately obvious to us. God could be working on a grander scale or in ways that are beyond our comprehension. Some believe that God's timing is different from ours.\n\n*   **Free will:** This perspective emphasizes that God has given humans the freedom to make their own choices, even if those choices lead to suffering. God might not intervene because doing so would violate our free will.\n\n*   **Tests of faith:** Some believe that suffering is a test of faith, and that God allows difficult things to happen to strengthen our character and draw us closer to God.\n\n*   **Natural laws:** Another view is that God created the universe with natural laws that govern how things work. These laws can sometimes result in events that cause suffering, but they are also necessary for the functioning of the universe.\n\n*   **God helps those who help themselves:** This idea suggests that God provides opportunities and resources, but it's up to us to take action and make a difference in the world.\n\n*   **God is not real:** Some people don't believe in God at all, or they believe that if God does exist, God is not all-powerful or all-good. From this perspective, there is no divine intervention because there is no intervening God.\n\nIt's important to acknowledge that there is no easy way to reconcile belief in a loving and all-powerful God with the existence of suffering in the world. This is known as the problem of evil, and it's a challenge that has been debated by theologians and philosophers for centuries.",
